      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Benchmark problems from NAFEMS and ASME V&V 10 suite must reproduce analytical solutions to within 1% for linear elastic beam bending; requiredLevel 2 consistent with medium-risk COU with corroborating physical tests.",
      "rationale": "Standard NAFEMS benchmarks executed confirming solver accuracy for contact-dominated structural problems. Patch test passed for all element formulations used. Results match analytical cantilever beam solutions within 0.4%, satisfying the 1% threshold."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Discretization error",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Mesh convergence study must demonstrate QoI change of less than 5% between successive refinement levels; Richardson extrapolation applied where feasible; requiredLevel 2 set for medium-risk device class with physical validation data available.",
      "rationale": "Three-level mesh refinement study performed on screw shank and rod-screw interface regions. QoI (construct stiffness) changed by 1.8% between medium and fine mesh; 0.6% between fine and extra-fine. Richardson extrapolation GCI < 2.1%. Achieved level 3 due to systematic convergence documentation exceeding minimum requirements."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Numerical solver error",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Residual force norms must converge below 1e-4 relative tolerance; contact penetration monitored and confirmed below 0.001 mm; requiredLevel 2 appropriate for medium model risk with physical corroboration.",
      "rationale": "Newton-Raphson iterations converged to force residual norm 8.3e-6 across all load steps. Augmented Lagrange contact algorithm used with penetration tolerance 0.0003 mm. No divergence events observed across 11-specimen parametric sweep."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Use error",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "rationale": "Model setup reviewed by two independent analysts (FDA and DePuy Synthes) following a documented simulation protocol. Boundary conditions, material assignments, and contact definitions cross-checked against the ASTM F1717 test fixture geometry. No discrepancies identified between the three modeling teams. RequiredLevel 2 reflects medium model influence; the structured acceptance criteria basis is captured in the simulation protocol SOP-SIM-042 revision C, which specifies that independent review by a second analyst constitutes the minimum acceptance threshold for this factor at the required gradation."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Model form",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Linear elastic material model acceptable for pre-yield regime; elasto-plastic Chaboche model required for post-yield; contact formulation must capture screw-rod interface slip; requiredLevel 3 reflects higher model-form sensitivity given nonlinear contact and material plasticity at large displacements.",
      "rationale": "Bilinear isotropic hardening assigned to titanium alloy (Ti-6Al-4V) screw and rod based on certified material coupon data. Linear elastic UHMWPE block model validated against literature compressive modulus. Frictional contact (mu=0.2) at screw-rod interface reproduces observed hysteresis in load-displacement curve. Model form uncertainty quantified via sensitivity analysis; dominant contributor is interface friction coefficient (±15% variation yields ±3.2% stiffness change)."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Model inputs",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Material properties sourced from certified lot-specific tensile test data or peer-reviewed literature with stated uncertainty; geometric inputs derived from CMM measurements with tolerance ±0.02 mm; requiredLevel 3 set because model-input uncertainty is the dominant source of total model uncertainty for this construct.",
      "rationale": "Ti-6Al-4V elastic modulus (114 GPa ± 2.1 GPa) and yield strength (880 MPa ± 12 MPa) from DePuy Synthes lot certificates. UHMWPE block modulus from ASTM D638 coupon tests (n=5, mean 0.93 GPa, CV 4.2%). Geometry from CMM scan of representative screw and rod; nominal vs. actual dimensions within 0.015 mm. Uncertainty propagation via Monte Carlo (10,000 samples) yielded 95th-percentile stiffness uncertainty of ±4.7%."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Test samples",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Minimum N=10 specimens required; specimens must be production-representative with documented lot traceability; dimensional inspection of each specimen required; requiredLevel 3 reflects importance of sample representativeness for a Class II device submission.",
      "rationale": "N=11 non-cannulated 7.5 mm pedicle screw constructs tested across two independent laboratories (FDA CDRH and DePuy Synthes). All specimens from production lots with full material and dimensional traceability. CMM inspection confirmed all specimens within engineering drawing tolerances. Between-laboratory reproducibility coefficient of variation 2.8% for stiffness."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Test conditions",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Multiple loading configurations (minimum two load angles or boundary condition variants) required to demonstrate model generalizability; requiredLevel 3 reflects the need to confirm model validity across the range of in vivo loading conditions represented by the COU.",
      "rationale": "Testing performed under a single ASTM F1717 compression-bending configuration (5-degree offset). Environmental conditions (ambient temperature 23±2°C, dry) standardized across both laboratories. Load rate 25 mm/min per protocol. Achieved level 2 because only one loading configuration was tested; the model has not been validated under alternative load angles or cyclic conditions. This limitation is acknowledged and accepted given that the COU is explicitly bounded to the F1717 static compression-bending scenario."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Equivalency of input parameters",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "rationale": "Model input parameters (geometry, material properties, boundary conditions, applied loads) confirmed equivalent to experimental test conditions through side-by-side comparison table documented in the validation report. Screw torque preload applied in simulation matched measured installation torque (mean 6.2 Nm, SD 0.3 Nm) using bolt pretension elements. UHMWPE block dimensions in model matched CMM-measured specimen dimensions within 0.01 mm. RequiredLevel 2 is set because model influence is medium and physical testing directly constrains the parameter space; the structured threshold is that all input parameters must be traceable to measured or certified values with no assumed defaults for primary load-path components. Achieved level 3 reflects the additional quantitative uncertainty bounding performed for each parameter."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Output comparison",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "All three QoIs (stiffness, yield force, force at 40 mm) must satisfy simultaneously: (1) mean FEA prediction within 10% of experimental mean, and (2) validation metric E/uval < 1.96; requiredLevel 3 reflects quantitative comparison requirement for a medium-risk Class II device.",
      "rationale": "Stiffness: FEA 187.4 N/mm vs. experimental mean 191.2 N/mm (−2.0%, E/uval=0.83). Yield force: FEA 312.1 N vs. experimental 318.6 N (−2.0%, E/uval=1.12). Force at 40 mm: FEA 428.7 N vs. experimental 435.1 N (−1.5%, E/uval=0.94). All three QoIs satisfy both acceptance criteria. Validation metric computed per ASME V&V 40 Section 5.3 incorporating experimental measurement uncertainty and model parameter uncertainty."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Relevance of the quantities of interest",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "QoIs must directly correspond to the regulatory submission metrics specified in the device predicate comparison; stiffness, yield force, and force at 40 mm displacement are the FDA-specified metrics for ASTM F1717; requiredLevel 2 reflects medium model influence where QoI relevance is confirmed by regulatory precedent.",
      "rationale": "The three QoIs (stiffness, yield force, force at 40 mm displacement) are the primary performance metrics specified in ASTM F1717 and referenced in FDA guidance for spinal implant 510(k) submissions. These QoIs directly inform the regulatory decision regarding construct mechanical performance equivalence to predicate. No surrogate or proxy quantities used. Achieved level 3 because QoI definitions were prospectively specified in the validation plan prior to data collection."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Relevance of the validation activities to the COU",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Validation scenario must replicate the COU geometry, loading, and boundary conditions with documented mapping; any differences between validation scenario and COU must be explicitly bounded; requiredLevel 3 reflects the need for high relevance given that model predictions directly support a regulatory submission.",
      "rationale": "Validation activities performed on production-equivalent non-cannulated 7.5 mm pedicle screw constructs under ASTM F1717 conditions, which is precisely the COU. The FEA model geometry, material assignments, and boundary conditions are identical between the validation simulation and the COU simulation. No extrapolation beyond validated conditions is claimed. The single-configuration limitation (Test conditions factor, achieved level 2) is explicitly scoped into the COU boundary, ensuring the validation activities remain fully relevant within that bounded scope."
    }
